  "remote_port": 443,
  "prompt": "What are some good probiotic foods I should add to my diet?",
  "response": "Incorporating probiotic-rich foods into your diet is a great way to support gut health. Here are some good options to consider:\n\n1. **Yogurt**: Look for yogurt with live and active cultures. It's a widely accessible source of probiotics and can be enjoyed on its own or added to smoothies.\n\n2. **Kefir**: This is a fermented milk drink similar to yogurt but with a thinner consistency. It contains a diverse range of probiotic strains.\n\n3. **Sauerkraut**: Made from fermented cabbage, sauerkraut is rich in probiotics as well as vitamins C and K. Choose unpasteurized versions to ensure it contains active bacteria.\n\n4. **Kimchi**: This is a spicy, fermented Korean side dish made from cabbage and other vegetables. It is seasoned with various spices and is packed with probiotics.\n\n5. **Miso**: A traditional Japanese seasoning produced by fermenting soybeans with salt and koji. Miso soup is a common way to consume it.\n\n6. **Tempeh**: Fermented soybeans form a cake-like protein source that is firm and grainy. It\u2019s rich in probiotics and protein.\n\n7. **Kombucha**: A fermented tea that is slightly fizzy and available in various flavors. It contains a variety of bacteria and yeasts that are beneficial for gut health.\n\n8. **Pickles**: Fermented in a brine made of water and salt, pickles that are not vinegar-based can offer probiotic benefits.\n\n9. **Natto**: A traditional Japanese food made from fermented soybeans. It has a strong flavor and sticky texture, packed with probiotics and vitamin K2.\n\n10. **Goat's Milk and Soft Cheeses**: Some cheeses, such as Gouda, mozzarella, and cheddar, contain probiotics. Check labels for \"live and active cultures.\"\n\nKeep in mind that individual tolerances vary, so it's best to introduce these foods gradually into your diet. Also, to ensure the health benefits, look for products that indicate they contain \"live and active cultures.\"",
